From: conao3 <conao3@gmail.com>
Subject: orchestrator: cap agent attempts per issue and force Cancelled on overshoot

Symphony's default retry policy spawns a fresh worker for every continuation
attempt as long as the Linear issue stays in an active state. With long
self-driving runs this lets a single scope-violating ticket (one Linear issue
that the agent cannot finish in a single PR) burn arbitrarily many attempts:
in bun-bunsai's 24h baseline a single issue went 62 sessions before the
operator manually intervened.

Add a per-issue attempt cap so the orchestrator can break the loop.

Two layers:

  Phase 1 - opportunistic self-cancel signal
    * New `agent.max_attempts_per_issue` config field (default 0 = disabled,
      preserving upstream behavior).
    * When the orchestrator is about to dispatch the cap'th attempt, it sets
      `final_attempt: true` and the PromptBuilder exposes it to the workflow
      template. WORKFLOW.md can branch on `{% if final_attempt %}` to tell the
      agent to stop implementing, record a workspace summary on the workpad,
      and move the issue to Cancelled.

  Phase 2 - hard gate
    * Agents in the wild ignore the `final_attempt` branch in ~98% of cases
      (618 final_attempt=true dispatches vs 10 self-Cancelled in our trace),
      so once `attempt > max_attempts_per_issue` the orchestrator stops
      spawning entirely and calls `Tracker.update_issue_state(id, "Cancelled")`
      itself, emitting a `CanceledByAttemptLimit` warning. The operator/planner
      then splits the work via the "Cancel-and-resplit" playbook
      (notes/playbook/operation-symphony.md).

Default value of 0 keeps upstream behavior untouched for users who do not opt
in. Tracker.update_issue_state is the same path Symphony already uses for
terminal transitions, so no new Linear API surface is required.

Related: bun-bunsai/.claude-dev/task-goal-000.md (token-reduction plan,
action A1) describes the rationale and target metrics.

